                        <additions>
                            <p>
                                <locus from="LCI" to="LCI" scheme="other"/>
                                <note>Top left corner, in pencil by a modern hand: the current signum of the <orgName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/org/100004">National Library</orgName>, <quote>A 92a</quote>; adjacent to this, in pencil by a modern hand: <quote>b 5 3</quote> (struck through); top centre, in pencil by a modern hand: the signum of the <orgName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/org/100187">Ötttingen-Wallerstein library</orgName>, <quote>II (Lat.) I 4o 42</quote>.</note>
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                <locus from="RCI" to="RCI" scheme="other"/>
                                <note>Centre page, <orgName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/org/100004">National Library</orgName> stamp; bottom page: two stamps from the <orgName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/org/100187">Ötttingen-Wallerstein library</orgName>.</note>
                            </p>
                        </additions>
                        <decoDesc>
                            <decoNote type="images">
                                <p>
                                    <locus from="LCI" to="LCI" scheme="other"/>, woodcut of St Birgitta standing with her customary symbols: a book, the pilgrim's staff, and hat; frame in black filled with floral ornaments; upper left corner, a coat of arms with <quote>SPQR</quote>. The print is coloured in red, green, pink/beige, and blueish grey. For a more detailed description, see <ref target="http://urn.kb.se/resolve?urn=urn:nbn:se:alvin:portal:record-472831">Lindqvist Sandgren</ref>.</p>
                            </decoNote>
                        </decoDesc>
                        <bindingDesc>
                            <binding contemporary="true">
                                <p> Medieval binding. White leather over bevelled wooden boards. 3 double raised bands and endbands. 1 hooked clasp with a white leather strap; both clasp and catchplate decorated with a floral motif. Lower left corner of <locus from="LCO" to="LCO" scheme="other"/>: National Library book label with current signum. <locus from="LCI" to="LCI" scheme="other"/>: paper pastedown glued on top of fragment from a 12th-century manuscript with neumes; <locus from="RCI" to="RCI" scheme="other"/>: fragment of same manuscript as on <locus from="LCI" to="LCI" scheme="other"/> glued on top of paper pastedown.</p>
                                <p>
                                    <dimensions type="binding">
                                        <height quantity="210" unit="mm"/>
                                        <width quantity="160" unit="mm"/>
                                        <depth quantity="30" unit="mm"/>
                                    </dimensions>
                                </p>
                                <condition>The leather binding has numerous wormholes and is worn, showing the wooden boards in a few places as well as the binding on the <locus from="Spine" to="Spine" scheme="other"/>. <locus from="LCO" to="LCO" scheme="other"/>: a hole from a centre boss. Remnants of three paper labels pasted around the <locus from="Spine" to="Spine" scheme="other"/>.</condition>
                            </binding>
                        </bindingDesc>
                    </physDesc>
                    <history>
                        <origin>
                            <p>
                                <origPlace>
                                    <placeName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100104">Germany</placeName>
                                    <placeName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100252">Maihingen</placeName>
                                </origPlace>, <origDate when="1499">1499</origDate>; see colophon on <locus from="68r" to="68r" scheme="folios"/>.</p>
                        </origin>
                        <provenance>
                            <p>The manuscript was most likely produced in the monastery of <orgName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/org/100160">Maria Maihingen</orgName> and remained there until the monastery's dissolution at the end of the 16th cenury (<bibl>
                                    <title type="short" ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/bibl/107292">Schier (2013)</title>
                                    <citedRange from="269" to="270" unit="page"/>
                                </bibl>). According to Schier, it then probably passed into the possession of the new Franciscan monastery at <placeName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100252">Maihingen </placeName>(ibid.). At the beginning of the 19th century it entered into<orgName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/org/100187"> the library of the princely family of Öttingen-Wallerstein</orgName> (cf. stamp on <locus from="RCI" to="RCI" scheme="other"/>), where it remained until <date when="1934"/>.</p>
                        </provenance>
                        <acquisition>
                            <p>Purchased by the <orgName>National Library</orgName> at auction in Halle in May <date when="1934">1934</date>.</p>
                        </acquisition>
                    </history>
